The simultaneous discovery of the planet Neptune by Adams and Le Verrier, as a result of the most elaborate mathematical investigations (to say nothing of the more familiar case of the prediction of eclipses), is alone a sufficient refutation of Bacon's view. F ormal Astronomy, or the consideration of the apparent motions of the heavenly bodies in Space and Time, was an essential prelude to Physical Astronomy, or the reference of these motions to their causes in Foroe and Matter.
